Guiding Question:

What variables are good predictors for the price of cars and which are good variables for the price of motorcycles?

Data Access

We begin by reading in the data files. Our first data file contains data regarding the price of cars and other variables such as make, fuel type, and doors. This data was posted by Eleanor Xu who posted it on Kaggle using Python. It was obtained 5 years ago from multiple open source datasets to analyze car prices and its variables. Data Link: URL: https://www.kaggle.com/jingbinxu/sample-of-car-data

Our second data file was gathered from Kaggle as well. It was posted by Nehal Birla who obtained it from multiple open source datasets in order to analyze motorcycle prices. She collected the data in 2020. It contains variables such as selling price, year, and seller type. URL: https://www.kaggle.com/nehalbirla/motorcycle-dataset

Data Wrangling

We performed a series of data wrangling to help us better understand the data and create better visualizations. These included regular expressions, user-defined functions, reduction/transformation functions, and pivots.

Convert owner’s data type

We decide to change the number of owners from a character to numeric variable. For example, one owner will become “1” and so on. This allows us to find the mean number of owners.

Bike <-
  Bike %>%
    mutate(owner = gsub(pattern = "[st,nd,rd,th]|owner", replacement = "", owner))
Bike$owner <- as.numeric(as.character(Bike$owner))

Finding the square inches of cars

sqr_length <- function(a,b,c){
  (a*b*c)
}
Cars$square_inches <- sqr_length(Cars$length,Cars$width,Cars$height)
intoft <- function(a){
  (a/12)
}
Cars$length_ft <- intoft(Cars$length)
Cars$width_ft <- intoft(Cars$width)
Cars$height_ft <- intoft(Cars$height)
Cars$square_inches <- sqr_length(Cars$length_ft,Cars$width_ft,Cars$height_ft)
Cars

We were interested in how the size of the cars contributed to the price of the cars. We used the above code to calculate the square inches of the cars by multiplying the length* width *height. Then we converted the inches to feet and calculated the square footage of the cars. The square footage, square inches, length in feet, width in feet, and height in feet were all added as columns to the data frame “Cars”. This will also be used visually later.

Prepare a subdata for aspiration visualization (regular expression and pivot)

### Prepare a subdata for brand visualization (regular expression and transfornmation function)

Cars <- Cars[Cars$price != '?',] #we want the cases with price only
Cars$price <- as.numeric(Cars$price)

Cars <- # adjust with currency exchange rate
  Cars %>%
  mutate(price = 1.2*price)

Make <-
  Cars %>%
  select(make, price) %>%
  group_by(make) %>%
  summarise(mean_price_New = mean(price,na.rm = T)) %>%
  mutate(valuegroup = if_else(mean_price_New > 30000, true = "> $30k",
                              false = if_else(mean_price_New >15000,
                                              true = "$30k-$15k",
                                              false = "< $15k"))) %>%
  # define price group for new cars
  arrange(desc(mean_price_New))

Aspiration <-
  Cars %>%
  group_by(make, aspiration) %>%
  summarise(total = mean(price)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = aspiration, values_from = total)
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'make'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Relationship between Price and Seller Type and Year in Motorcycles

Next we analyze if owner and year can influence the price of motorcycles.

Bike%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = selling_price)) + geom_point() + facet_grid( ~ seller_type)  + ylab("Price of Motorcycle") + xlab("Year of Motorcycle") + ggtitle("Price of Motorcycle by Seller Type and Year")

From this graph, we can see that as a motorcycle increases year, the price increases This is likely due to the wear that is put on an older motorcycle. Older motorcycles have a lower price while newer ones have higher ones. We cannot say that seller type can influence price. There is not information to say that it would be true. However, Year and Price have a positive linear relationship.

We find that owners is not entirely a good predictor. The data is a bit inconsistent because bikes with 3 owners have a cheaper price than those with 2. This is not entirely logically true. Therefore, we cannot say it is a good predictor.

Conclusion

We find that the following variables are good for predicting price in cars:

Manufacturers: Luxury brand manufacturers are more likely to have more expensive cars. Square Inches: Size and price have a positive linear relationship. Larger cars aare more likely to be expensive because they provide more room.

We find that the following variables are good for predicting price in motorcycles:

Manufacturers: The manufacturer is a good predictor due to manufacturers having a localized price point for their vehicles. There are luxury manufacturers and cheaper manufacturers. Seller Type: Year: Year is also a good indicator of price. This is due slightly because of inflation, but mainly because newer motorcycles will cost more than older models. Kilometers Driven: Kilometers driven has a negative correlation with price, because the more a motorcycle has been driven the lower it’s value will become.

Not so good variables for predicting price in motorcycles:

Seller type: This is not a good indicator of price of motorcycles. This is due to there not being a large change in price based on if the motorcycle is sold by a dealer or by an individual. Number of owners: This is not a good indicator of price for motorcycle price because of the conflicting data that there are both positive and negative reasons for a person to sell their motorcycle (rarity, problems)
